<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-159-369 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 808 640</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  May 6 1991 v8 n9 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Server-based backup system is a smart strategy. (LAN Primer)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Germann, Christopher.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The necessity of tape backup for network servers is now considereda given; the location of that backup, however, is not.andP;  Theincreasing presence of client/server and peer-to-peer software hasraised questions in some users' minds as to whether that backupshould be located on the server or on a workstation.andP;  Proponentsof workstation-based backup who argue that server-based backup isunavailable if the server goes down miss the point that backup isintended for disaster recovery, not fault-tolerance.andP;  Others citeinterference with the server's processing overhead, but this canbe overcome by setting server-based applications at a lowerpriority level.andP;  Server-based tape backup runs faster and moreefficiently than workstation backup, and is more secure.andP;  The mainadvantages of workstation-based backup are convenience andreduction of maintenance and troubleshooting costs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Back-Up SystemsFile ServersWorkstationsComparisonEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>